<div id="review_75326863" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/75326863" />
    <a title="Paul Fidalgo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1228813-paul-fidalgo"><img alt="Paul Fidalgo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1497492437p2/1228813.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/75326863?book_show_action=true">Oct 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul Fidalgo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul Fidalgo" href="/user/show/1228813-paul-fidalgo">Paul Fidalgo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer75326863" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2628092371016642867">Excerpt: Part of what makes this book less compelling is its lack of unity of purpose. There are chapters focused on debunking attacks from religionists and theologians, then sections summarizing some of the more influential religious and philosophical movements, all peppered with a surprising amount of synopses of his previous works as well as other people&apos;s. Though when tackling a subject, Stenger can be refreshingly succinct and sharp, the book as an experience lacks a flow that leads the rea</span>
  <span id="freeText2628092371016642867" style="display:none">Excerpt: Part of what makes this book less compelling is its lack of unity of purpose. There are chapters focused on debunking attacks from religionists and theologians, then sections summarizing some of the more influential religious and philosophical movements, all peppered with a surprising amount of synopses of his previous works as well as other people's. Though when tackling a subject, Stenger can be refreshingly succinct and sharp, the book as an experience lacks a flow that leads the reader anywhere in particular. Stenger also makes an odd habit of insinuating his own works into the existing New Atheist pantheon (pardon the term)--while I have no quibbles with him being considered a "Fifth Horseman," it was a little uncomfortable to read several times that he seemed to think that anyone else thought him so. This is not in any way to denigrate the value of his work and contributions, but merely a comment on his choice to write about them in this particular manner. Also somewhat jarring is Stenger's fairly awkward use of more colloquial language that often seems to come from nowhere, and feel out of place in the context of the grand ideas being discussed.<br /><br />For the full review, visit my column at <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.examiner.com/examiner/x-4275-Secularism-Examiner~y2010m1d15-Book-Review-Stengers-New-Atheism--Uneven-but-uncompromising">http://www.examiner.com/examiner/x-42...</a>#</span>
  <a data-text-id="2628092371016642867" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


