<div id="review_74017251" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/74017251" />
    <a title="Tracy Black" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1780231-tracy-black"><img alt="Tracy Black" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1231099457p2/1780231.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/74017251?book_show_action=true">Oct 09, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tracy Black" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tracy Black" href="/user/show/1780231-tracy-black">Tracy Black</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer74017251" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4386211044789517748">Parts of this books were excellent and other parts were boring. It was still worth reading because he goes through the history of the new atheism movement, concentrating mostly on the books published, and then discusses the rebuttals (i.e. The Dawkins&apos; Delusion). The boring parts were tangents that didn&apos;t fit the theme of the book, like a Newtonian physics lesson that didn&apos;t go anywhere.</span>
  <span id="freeText4386211044789517748" style="display:none">Parts of this books were excellent and other parts were boring. It was still worth reading because he goes through the history of the new atheism movement, concentrating mostly on the books published, and then discusses the rebuttals (i.e. The Dawkins' Delusion). The boring parts were tangents that didn't fit the theme of the book, like a Newtonian physics lesson that didn't go anywhere.</span>
